postcontent:
We may do some SHORT TERM financing on this weapon. Please inquire. This an original MAC .380 M-II. It is not an RPB parts gun. Nor is it a common gun like the .45s and 9mms. It is the smallest machine gun ever made. Comes with an SWD .380 suppressor and 3 magazines. Needs to be transfered on a Form 4. Registered in Ohio. It's .380. MAC marked the first 50 or so guns they made in .380 as 9mm Auto. They made few of these guns and sold them just as marked. This issue of gun was made in a failed attempt by MAC to interest the CIA in these because of it's extremely small size. The mags only hold .380 and 9mm will not fit. I have been involved with Machine guns for nearly 40 years and have only seen 2 genuine MACs like this. Years later RPB bought a bunch of incomplete frames from MAC and made a similar gun that had their name on it. This is the smallest and rarest machine gun ever made. title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson J Round Conversion Grips Sile Italy GRsilSQJD New Old Stock converts J Frame Round Butt to Square Butt Contour Feel Magna Service Diamond
postcontent:
Our # GRsilSQJD, Grips for S&W J Frame Round Butt Revolvers Sile Walnut Square Butt Conversion Grips 1980s Production As New Smith & Wesson Models 34 36 37 38 40 42 637 638 640 642 317 651

This listing is for One Set of Grips. Buyers, however, may take any number of additional small light similar items on the same order and it will not add anything to your shipping costs. Most Smith & Wesson Revolvers manufactured after 1996 have Round Butt Grip Frames. If you aren’t sure which yours is, please see the comparative photo. Photos show representatives of only a handfull Italian Walnut grips we found in an old Southern Warehouse for any Smith & Wesson J frame revolver with a round butt grip frame. These include models 34 and 36, and their stainless counterparts models 63 and 60. These are excellent grips, and we sold lots of them during the 1960s until 1980s. These were imported by distinguished New York Importer Sile, Inc., and all of them are new, just occasionally with some slight signs of shelfwear from their years in the warehouse. They are in their boxes, but the glue is dry and the boxes show some separation. Their interior wrapping paper is old and brittle, but the grips themselves are pristine, never opened. What these do, shooting wise, is to increase the size of the grip on a J-Round and give the shooter better control, whether for target shooting with a round butt 4 inch Model 34-1, or in Combat situations under stress for concealable revolvers. These grips’s heyday in the 1970s and 1980s saw them compete favorably with the much pricier factory Smith & Wesson grips that were hard to get at the time for any price. This was before the days of boot grips, but with a set of these Magna style Service grips and a Tyler T Grip adapter, a person had an excellent means to hold a revolver that current production boot grips simply cannot match. Some of our photos show the grip frame of a 1968 Airweight Bodyguard with a set installed. We strongly recommend inspection and fitting where the revolver’s grip frame makes contact. These are all genuine diamond pattern checkered Italian Walnut with nickel plated screws and screw escutcheons. These grips are period correct for any Smith & Wesson manufactured from the late 1960s through about 1995, and we consider them collectable in their own right. They will fit all current production variants of the J Frame Round Butt revolvers. We’re offering these fine grips well below what similar bizarre looking competitors sell for. Own a set, the ones in the photos or a set of their identical mates for only $ 39.00.

title: For Sale:  Rossi .357 Magnum model 461 Blue Steel 2 inch 6 Shot DAO Bobbed Hammer Excellent in Box Factory Demo Walnut Grips Discontinued S&W K Colt D Frame type R46112U
postcontent:
Our # HGR46112U

Photos are representative, but buyers will receive a virtually identical specimen to the one in the photos. Dealers, collectors, and law enforcement, however, may take any number of virtually identical 461s we have on hand at the same per-gun price and with no additional shipping charges. Any ammunition showing in our photos is Not Included. Most of the Rossis we sold in the 1960s were model 31 series; there were only a few of the medium frame model 51s that came through. While the Brazilians used Smith & Wesson Hand Ejector milling equipment during that period, and their mechanical designs were close to Smith & Wessons, the model 51 had a Colt Influence as well. This descendant of the model 51 is close to the Colt D frame Detective Specials of the late 1960s and early 1970s, with 6 shot cylinder and shrouded ejector rod. Here is the model R461 that is .357 Magnum capable. Manufacturer is Amadeo Rossi of Sao Leopoldo, Brazil, a Taurus affiliate; this .38 is marked Made In Brazil By Taurus on the right side of its frame. Type is double action only revolver. The hammer does not stand in a cocked position. Construction is entirely blue steel with the exception of the hardened stainless steel hammer nose firing pin and rivet. Frame is D Size small frame, with Round Butt Grip frame and 3 screw side plate. Barrel is 2 inch heavy full lug type, with matte finish verticals and barrel-integral serrated blade front sight. Rear sight is frame integral fixed notch. Cylinder capacity is 6 rounds of .357 Remington Magnum and .38 Smith & Wesson Special calibers. Note the cylinder yoke’s detent latch, a Taurus inspired mechanical improvement that prevents cylinder wobble. Trigger is .380 smooth faced combat semi-target, with factory bobbed .265 smooth hammer. Weight empty is a well balanced 23 1/2 ounces with center of gravity at the trigger. Double action trigger pull is smooth and consistent, 10 pound vicinity. Safety system consists of a transfer bar that prevents the firing pin from touching a cartridge primer unless the trigger is fully depressed, and also Taurus’s innovative internal hammer lock. Note that we have installed a set of Sile Italian Walnut Banana Style Grips for Smith & Wesson J Frame Round Butt, modified and fitted to this Rossi. The Siles were production mates to the ones still found on many Smith & Wessson J and Colt D frame revolvers manufactured in the 1970s and 1980s. Note that an H.K.S. DSA Speedloader Will Not clear the left panel’s recess. From its letter G serial number prefix, this 461 was manufactured in 2012 or 2013. This revolver is what we call a factory demo, probably a sales rep’s sample or showgirl from Firearms Industry trade shows like the annual SHOT show held in Las Vegas. Serial number’s X prefix designates it as such. It is in its original overlabeled factory box with instruction manual, two keys for its hammer lock and its never executed factory registration card. Note that the box top is labeled, Factory Reconditioned. This simply means that if this Rossi develops mechanical problems, Braztech will repair it at no charge, but they will not give a freebie refinish. It does not need any refinish anyway. Surface detractions are negligible, only faint occasional edge whitening and cylinder rotation marking. We rate this R461 as Excellent in Box, perhaps Near Mint, but photos ought to suffice for our distinguished shoppers to judge finish grade for themselves. Bore, chamber, and mechanism are all bright and clean. The only comparable Blue Steel 2 inch 6 shot revolver on the market is the Taurus 605 series, with their prices usually approaching $500 per unit; and two times that for a Colt Detective Special. We’re offering the Rossi R461 Blue 2 inch in the photos, however, or one of its virtually identical mates	 	for only	$ 319.00. title: For Sale:  Winchester 1894 Made in 1908 Rare 25-35 WCF
postcontent:
An elderly lady friend who belongs to my church, and is on a very fixed income, has decided it is time to part with some of her late husbands treasures.
I am not a gun expert so I will tell you all I know from research.
This is a very nice vintage Winchester Model 1894 saddle ring (missing the actual ring) carbine in the hard to find 25-35 WCF caliber. 
Made in 1908 it has the standard 20 inch carbine barrel.
It has (I believe) the original rear sight, but had a “Marble” tang sight added with the matching copper blade front sight.
The bore has good rifling with some wear/frosting/slight pitting, but the gun smith I had clean it up said it should not really effect shooting it.
The gun has been re-blued at some point during its very long life and looks very good, but there is slight pitting on the barrel. 
The receiver is mechanically excellent, feeds chambers and ejects properly. The action is extremely smooth and slick when you cycle the bolt, one of the great features of these old pre WW1 Winchesters! 
The screw head slots are all clean and sharp, they do not appear to have been turned. 
The buttstock and forearm are tight and solid, no cracks, chips, extra holes or other damage, just honest wear and minor dings from over 100 years of use. 
The metal butt plate has some rust pitting from where it sat in the gun case.
The wood does not appear to have been sanded, although at some point someone decided to add, what I would call “folk art” to the butt. 
Overall I would say this is a good tight 1908 carbine that has seen honest use, but not abuse, and was enjoyed by her late husband.
He also seems to have been a reloader. It comes with 70 shell casings, 2 actual rounds (the 20 round ammo boxes have a price tag on them of $5.59 and $6.27....oh the good old days!!!)and a box from RCBS Gun and Die shop with two "reloading dies"...I guess that is what they are.
I will be glad to send any additional photos that you may want to see.
As I said, I am no gun expert, all I have done is research what I could find online that are similar to this rifle. What I have found is, I cannot find one exactly like this. 
For one thing it seems 30-30 is pretty common. 
25-35, not so much.
1908’s not too many. 
Saddle ring, not too many. 
With Marble tang sight? Very few. 
Prices of course vary from one to the other.
So, I am going to start out asking $2,000.00 for this gun. I do not want to lowball it and lose money for my friend. If you think that is too much, let me know. 
I am not 100% firm on that price!
Feel free to let me know if you do not think it is enough too! 
Right…I’m sure that will happen.

title: For Sale:  Silencerco Osprey 9mm Suppressor
postcontent:
Silencerco’s Osprey family of pistol suppressors is a perfect blend of form and function. With the modern combat handgun in mind, Silencerco set out to create a silencer that performs well and looks like it belongs—the best possible marriage between host weapon and silencer. Silencerco went to work to make a suppressor that maximizes sound suppression levels, allows the use of more host pistols with factory sights, and has more operationally friendly features. What was created was the Osprey pistol silencer available for 9mm, .40 S&W, and 45ACP. Although round silencers are very effective for many applications, for a centerfire handgun round it has its limits. To obtain the most suppression, silencers must have as much internal volume as possible; but for a round tubular silencer, the only way to acquire more internal volume is by increasing the overall diameter and/or length. Increasing a tube’s diameter will obscure the site picture of the host gun and inhibit the possibility of holstering a weapon with the silencer still attached to the host gun. The Osprey is an eccentric silencer, which means that the bore does not run down the middle of the tube. Because of this eccentric design, most of the baffles and internal volume is beneath the centerline of the bore and out of the way of the gun’s sights, thus leaving the shooter the ability to use factory sights with little or no sight or target obstruction. The Osprey has flat side walls and angled edges that mimic many modern combat handgun slides and is just slightly wider than most host pistols. This feature allows the host weapon to be holstered with many popular open bottom holster designs with Osprey attached. The Osprey contains approximately 30% more internal volume than a traditional round tube silencer at the same length, but does so without obscuring the shooter’s sight picture or adding excessive width and length. 9 OSPREY CALIBER: 9MM Luger .300 BLK Subsonic WEIGHT: 9.8 OZ DIMENSIONS: 1.30”W × 1.75”H LENGTH: 7.0625” SOUND LEVEL: Dry: 125 dB (tested with a Sig 226 with American Eagle AE9FP 147 Grain Ammunition) FINISH: Hard Coat Anodizing Black Oxide MATERIALS: Core/Caps: 7075 T6 Aluminum Tube: 6061 T6 Aluminum Piston/Mounting System: 17-4 Stainless Steel, Heat Treated, Mount:Threads FEATURES: Interchangeable pistons Unobstructed sight picture Patented cam lock Mounting system Lifetime warranty MSRP: $849.95 (with piston)

title: For Sale:  Huntertown Arms Kestrel 556
postcontent:
Up until now, user serviceable centerfire rifle suppressors have been longer and heavier than their sealed counterparts. That's changed with the introduction of the Kestrel 5.56. Engineered from the ground up to maximize serviceability while not compromising on weight, length, or strength, the Kestrel 556 provides the most user friendly centerfire rifle suppressor in existence. Whether you are looking for outstanding suppression, safety, ease of maintenance, weight, length, longevity, or price, the Kestrel 5.56 has the features you are looking for.

Suppression

The Kestrel 5.56 had one goal - provide a hearing safe centerfire rifle suppressor that can be easily maintained and repaired. It does not disappoint.

Maintenance

Cleaning the Kestrel 5.56 is a breeze. Centerfire rifle suppressors need to be cleaned and inspected, just like rimfire suppressors. With the Kestrel 5.56 full user servicability is truely a reality. The Kestrel core is constructed of stainless steel for superior cleanability. You can use chemical solutions safe to stainless steel but that remove nasty lead deposits (the "Dip"). The core breaks down so that you can put it into a reloading tumbler, or use a bead blaster for fast and efficient cleaning. And unlike other monocore technologies, you can dip your Kestrel core without worrying about damaging the exposed finish on your core. Kestrel baffles are fully encased for superior strength and to prevent lead and carbon buildup between the core and the tube, even after thousands of rounds fired. This provides for quick and easy removal of your Kestrel core, without the hassle or need of pushers or other devices to remove it. And as with all Huntertown Arms suppressors, all it takes to remove your end caps is a standard, box end, or crescent wrench, a bench vise, pair of pliers, or any other tool that can grab a standard socket. No special tools required. Ever.

Longevity

There are several features designed into the Kestrel to ensure your safe and enjoyable use of the Kestrel beyond a lifetime. Most bullet strikes on a suppressor occur on the end cap. The Kestrel design separates the end cap from the registered part so that if there is an end cap strike it will be more likely your suppressor can be repaired or replaced without having to replace the registered part. We are huge proponents of stacked baffle technology for another reason. With a monocore, there is only one blast baffle. When that blast baffle erodes, the core has to be replaced. This may or may not be a warranty repair, but in any event you have lost the use of your suppressor while it is at the manufacturer for repair. Kestrel core baffles should be rotated (like tires) whenever the core is cleaned. With four baffles available to act as blast baffles, the Kestrel will allow up to five times the number of rounds fired before re-coring.

Safety

The Kestrel core is fully encased in an inner stainless steel wall. In the event of an internal baffle strike, the inner core is strong enough to capture the damaged projectile and baffle material, protecting the tube as much as possible against catastrophic failure.

Specifications

Supported Calibers:	5.56, 5.45, 5.7, 22 Hornet, .22LR, .22WMR, 17 HMR, 17 Mach 2 Full Auto:	Yes Minimum barrel length	11.5 inches Overall Length:	6.5 inches Diameter:	1.5 inches Weight:	19.5 ounces (plus mount) Core Material:	Stainless Steel Tube Material: Stainless Steel Finish:	Black Oxide Threads:	1/2-28, 1/2-36, 5/8-24 An optional universal mount is available for gunsmith fitting to any other thread pitch, including 24x1.5mm MSRP: $499.00

Warranty

Huntertown Arms warrants its suppressors for life against everything but stupid.

Purchase here: http://www.mcssl.com/store/f0abce2ec0a346dfbcac3621e92708/kestrel-556
